HEADWORD: Frow
<hw>Frow</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>vrouw</ets>;
akin to G. <ets>frau</ets> woman, wife, goth, <ets>fr⟦aacute⟧uja</ets>
master, lord, AS. <ets>fre⟦aacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
woman; especially, a Dutch or German woman.</def> <rj><au>Beau. &
Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dirty woman; a slattern.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frow
<hw>Frow</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Frower</er>.]</ety> <def>A cleaving tool with handle at right angles
to the blade, for splitting cask staves and shingles from the block; a
frower.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frow</ent>⟦br⟧

